import random   # start by importing the random module because we want the location of the cars to random on the plot
                # but how we gonna know the size? well let's see if the picture can tell the story.

    
# on this section we collecting variables that we need for our story

small = car_data.loc[car_data['Type'] == 'Small', ['Length', 'Width', 'Make']]

large = car_data.loc[car_data['Type'] == 'Large', ['Length', 'Width', 'Make']]

sporty = car_data.loc[car_data['Type'] == 'Sporty', ['Length', 'Width', 'Make']]

van = car_data.loc[car_data['Type'] == 'Van', ['Length', 'Width', 'Make']]

midsize = car_data.loc[car_data['Type'] == 'Midsize', ['Length', 'Width', 'Make']]

compact = car_data.loc[car_data['Type'] == 'Compact', ['Length', 'Width', 'Make']]



# and over here we creating some random numbers for the x_axis

v=list(range(0,len(van['Make'])))
random.shuffle(v)

sa=list(range(0,len(small['Make'])))
random.shuffle(sa)

l=list(range(0,len(large['Make'])))
random.shuffle(l)
                                                            # so what is actually happening here is: because need the x_axis to match 
                                                            # the y_axis we use the length of our data(s) and create the x_axis but randomly
                                                            # does that make sense?  if not just check the plot and see if the data is unable to tell the story despite their random position
c=list(range(0,len(compact['Make'])))
random.shuffle(c)

m=list(range(0,len(midsize['Make'])))
random.shuffle(m)

sp=list(range(0,len(sporty['Make'])))
random.shuffle(sp)


# so we gonna just have 1 column and 1 row but we just gonna make our figure a little bit bigger to fit our  data 
plt.figure(figsize=(20,20)) #i think 20*20 is fine for my screen but feel free to change the size if it doesn't fit your screen


#now let's see what is happening in our scatter plot... (by the way if you did not think we were going to use scatter again! well you just find out.)
#the only thing that looks dodgy in this plot is the s=argument or size. well I can explain;
#remember the crazy idea of shuffing the x_axis and see how the data is gonna tell its story, well, the secret lies in the size of 
#the dot which turns out to a BUBBLE therefore giving me a an excuse of using the scatter plot again because in this case we can call it a BUBBLE chart

plt.scatter(sa, small['Make'], s=(small[['Length','Width']].sum(axis=1)-180)**2, alpha=.5,label='Small')

plt.scatter(c, compact['Make'], s=(compact[['Length','Width']].sum(axis=1)-180)**2, alpha=.5, label='Compact')

plt.scatter(sp, sporty['Make'], s=(sporty[['Length','Width']].sum(axis=1)-180)**2, alpha=.5, label= 'Sporty')

plt.scatter(v, van['Make'], s=(van[['Length','Width']].sum(axis=1)-180)**2, alpha=.5, label="Van")

plt.scatter(m, midsize['Make'], s=(midsize[['Length','Width']].sum(axis=1)-180)**2, alpha=.5, label='Midsize')

plt.scatter(l, large['Make'], s=(large[['Length','Width']].sum(axis=1)-180)**2, alpha=.5, label='Large')




plt.ylabel('MAKE', color='r')

plt.title('SIZE OF CARS BY TYPE BASED ON LENGTH AND WIDTH')

plt.legend(loc=9,  ncol=6)

plt.grid(True)
